Dear Recruiter Name (Manager on Copy)\
First - thank you so much for the offer, I am very excited to join this company and now that I\'92ve had time to review the offer, I just had a few questions.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa388\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 ( I\'92m using this as an opportunity to demonstrate good faith. I\'92m showing gratitude for the\'a0offer, reinforcing my interest and making the negotiation a simple matter of \'91questions\'92 )\cf3 \strokec3 \
During the interview, we were working with a range of $180-$200k base salary.\'a0 The offer made was at $188k base. Knowing internal parity is important, I\'92d like to request the salary be closer in the $195-$205k range, this both reflects the value of my recent experience bringing data and numerics into HR workforce modeling as well as my significant experience helping senior leaders organize a high performing workforce.\
\cf4 \strokec4 ( I\'92m first documenting and establishing the range we had been working with, confirming what the offer was made for base salary and responding. Though I gave a range of 20k at the onset, since we are at offer I want to close this and aim for a little higher than the max of the range we were discussing. This means the response will likely be at $200k. I\'92m also backing up my point with a business case that immediately describes my value)\cf3 \strokec3 \
The bonus of 20% is very acceptable to the role.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa388\partightenfactor0

\f2\i \cf4 \strokec4 ( Performance bonuses are usually tied to a level and profile and can\'92t be negotiated with. Since bonuses are dependent\'a0on business success, it\'92s very possible that the company will pay below or above the bonus, so the target really doesn\'92t matter)
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
On the equity piece, seeing how this company stock has fluctuated somewhat recently, I\'92d like to increase the shares from 1000 to 1500 to account for any possibility of continued decline, especially considering the announcement made by your competitor this week, as well as the current financials made in your last quarterly call. By my calculations this is a difference of about $100,000 or almost $25,000 over the 4 year vesting schedule.\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa388\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 (While I always push to negotiate on salary, if you are joining a larger company and the role is eligible for equity, this is where some serious extra income can be found, so push as hard as you can. In this example, I\'92m also demonstrating my familiarity with equity plans and the monetary value, while also showing I\'92m very aware of the current market conditions to the company)\'a0\cf3 \strokec3 \
Finally, by accepting this offer, I will lose out on a 401k vest of approximately $28,000. Is it possible to have this gap included through a sign-on bonus? I understand it will have a clawback agreement of course.\'a0
\f2\i \'a0
\f0\i0 \
\cf4 \strokec4 (Many people misunderstand the purpose of a sign-on or signing bonus. There are typically only granted in the case of someone who loses money by taking the new offer)\cf3 \strokec3 \
Overall, I\'92m very excited to join and I\'92ve told other locations I am interviewing with that I have received an offer from an ideal company.\'a0
\f2\i \'a0\'a0
\f0\i0 \
\cf4 \strokec4 (I\'92m reminding the company that I am still considered an in play candidate, while not applying too much pressure. I\'92m also demonstrating that they would be my primary choice)\cf3 \strokec3 \
With almost 15 years of experience in HR, 10 of them as a Business Partner with large technology companies, I\'92m confident in my ability to deliver a great deal of value, starting with the Comp Modeling and increasing the feedback culture that were discussed in the interview.\
\cf4 \strokec4 \'a0(The biggest mistake people make is they don\'92t include references from the interview! Remember salaries and compensation are a business cost, so the best way to get a negotiation in your favor is to talk about your business value)\cf3 \strokec3 \
I believe we are almost close, but if we can get closer to the ranges I\'92ve given, I can sign this offer with complete confidence.\'a0
\f2\i \'a0
\f0\i0 \
\cf4 \strokec4 (This again re-affirms my good faith and sends the hidden signal to recruiters that they love to hear as they are singularly interested in closing the req)\cf3 \strokec3 \
