\cf3 \ul \ulc3 Frequent Questions and Myths\ulnone \
Q: What was the final offer?\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa388\partightenfactor0

\f2\i \cf4 \strokec4 A: The base salary was $195k, they increased the stock to 13,500 and provided a sign-on bonus of $25,000. The value of the first offer was almost $425k and the second was $500k, for a delta of almost $75k or 18%
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa388\partightenfactor0
\cf3 Q: Should you do this over email or over the phone?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa388\partightenfactor0

\f2\i \cf4 \strokec4 A: I am a firm believer that all negotiations should be done over email as it gives you these following benefits:
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf4 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 It reduces the pressure to accept and gives you an opportunity to put together your thoughts and business case\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf4 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 In many cases offers have to be reviewed by a number of people, especially if there is an exception. Having it in email means all of us can just weigh in on the same email thread.\'a0\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0\cf4 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 There are a lot of components to a job offer - this is just compensation and we already have four elements in play. Add in things like start-date, location, title, manager name, orientation schedule, etc and it\'92s therefore a lot easier to keep track of all the details and prevent simple mistakes\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0\cf4 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 AND MOST CRITICAL. This CREATES A SYSTEM OF RECORD. How many times have you heard horror stories saying: \'93They promised a 10% raise after 6 months\'85\'94 If it\'92s not in writing, it didn\'92t happen.\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa388\partightenfactor0
\cf3 Q: But Gary Voss\'85\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa388\partightenfactor0

\f2\i \cf4 \strokec4 A: I know - anytime I talk about negotiation, this is what people usually bring up. You have to remember though, an employment contract is very different from a transaction. The methodologies and perspective of buyer and seller for a house are very different from the perspectives of an employee and an employer. Take his information and synthesize it but realize that without any experience in HR or Compensation, there is no way to validate or verify any of his information.\'a0
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
Q: Why is the company offering me more than the range I gave?\

\f2\i \cf4 \strokec4 A: It\'92s a common myth that companies are looking to save money on your headcount. The truth is that you can cost anywhere from 2-3x your base salary in all of the other costs such as insurance, technology, payroll, worker\'92s compensation, etc. If the company wanted to save money, they wouldn\'92t open the headcount. Most companies want all employees to be paid fairly within a range to maintain peer equity. We actually get very excited when someone loves the offer we make.\'a0
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
Q: The recruiter said a few times that the company doesn\'92t negotiate, should I still try?\

\f2\i \cf4 \strokec4 A: At your own risk - a lot of companies are starting to view a no-negotiation policy because of how out of hand negotiation culture has become. It\'92s not wise to start with any ill-will when accepting an offer.\'a0
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
Q: I read somewhere that if the company wants to make you an offer, you have all the negotiating power and you should ask 20-30% above the range\

\f2\i \cf4 \strokec4 A: Before you ever take Compensation advice, verify who the person is and what experience they have. If they\'92ve never worked in HR or Recruiting, any of their advice becomes suspect as they have no experience to speak of, just their own personal anecdotes. This tactic is a surefire way to destroy your relationship with the recruiter who now has to try and salvage someone and look like an idiot to a hiring manager.\'a0
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
Q: What are all of the things I can negotiate?\

\f2\i \cf4 \strokec4 A: Some people love negotiating and will try to do every single element. Others are not so inclined. Generally speaking things like title, benefits, PTO and 401k shouldn\'92t be attempted, especially for medium or larger size companies. There are universal policies applicable to everyone and there\'92s simply no negotiation to happen. For smaller companies or start-ups, it\'92s more in your best interest to try and negotiate other elements.\'a0 I usually only recommend negotiating the elements of the offer that have a monetary value.
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
Q: What is Total Compensation?\

\f2\i \cf4 \strokec4 A: Total Compensation refers to the sum of all the monetary elements to an offer: Base, bonus, stock, sign-on bonus, relocation bonus, etc. Essentially anything that has a direct monetary value
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
Q: Is that the same as Total Rewards?\

\f2\i \cf4 \strokec4 A: No. Total rewards is the comprehensive amount of all monetary and non-monetary elements. Such as benefits, 401k, PTO, discounts and perks. For an offer, you are just focusing on Total Compensation.\'a0
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
Q: I\'92ve interviewed with this company I really like, but they say they can\'92t increase the offer, but it\'92s just not enough for me. Why are they under-valuing me?\

\f2\i \cf4 \strokec4 A: It can be tough to have this perspective, but over-time it\'92s best to realize that companies aren\'92t trying to judge you with their pay. It\'92s simply a value they\'92ve attached to this position and their assumption of how you can perform in it based on your interview. If the offer is low, simply decline it politely and wish them well.\'a0
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
Q: Why did the recruiter get a little cold when I refused to answer what range I was looking for? Aren\'92t I supposed to ask for a budget?\

\f2\i \cf4 \strokec4 A: No, this is horrible advice and consider not taking anyone that says this seriously. While you CAN bring up compensation first, if you don\'92t and the recruiter asks, doing this will usually work against you. It shows a lack of awareness on your part that the compensation will be based on your merit and experience and instead you just expect to be paid at the higher range. Do not do this.\'a0
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
Q: I tried to negotiate a higher base, but instead the company just gave me a relatively larger sign-on. That\'92s better, right?\

\f2\i \cf4 \strokec4 A: While it may make sense at first, the truth is a large sign-on is a very weak element to an offer. Not only will the taxes be greater, but it\'92s a one time value add. It is FAR more valuable to try and pump the base as much as possible. This is because bonuses, merit increases, market adjustments and promotion calculations are computed against the base.\'a0
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
Q: Shouldn\'92t I talk about Glassdoor or the market as part of the offer? Glassdoor said that my pay should be at $95k, but the company only offered me $75k\

\f2\i \cf4 \strokec4 A: Remember, Glassdoor and other websites like Blind, Salaries.com, Payscale, etc go by\'a0
\f0\i0 \strokec2 employee reported data.\'a0
\f2\i \strokec4 This means nobody is validating or auditing it. Also remember that companies can choose how much they want to pay for any position. Just because one company pays that amount does not mean all companies do.\'a0
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
Q: I\'92m interviewing for a few companies - one just made me an offer, but it\'92s not my first choice. Can I use that as leverage to get more from the next company\

\f2\i \cf4 \strokec4 A: To a small degree, yes, but just remember companies are far wiser to know when candidates are offer-shopping and offer ping-ponging. You want to be paid more for your value and experience, not because another company might offer you more.\'a0 Do this at your own risk and don\'92t be surprised if all companies simultaneously retract their offers.\'a0
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
Q: Can I try and find people on LinkedIn to see how much the salary should be?\

\f2\i \cf4 \strokec4 A: You can certainly try, but it\'92s just a huge waste of effort in my opinion. You will have no way to validate anything they say and it could be a difference in everything from level, location, tenure or including/excluding bonuses or stock. It\'92s much better to just ask the company directly
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
Q: Thank you for the template and TikToks! I see you offer a personal compensation guide - what is that?\

\f2\i \cf4 \strokec4 A: As someone who is uniquely qualified to talk about how most medium to large sized companies handle compensation, I do offer my personal services. This means I\'92ll do a great deal of research into the industry, company and use my private access to survey data to provide you with optimal information.\'a0
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \

\f2\i \cf4 \strokec4 I\'92ll also prep you with the best scripts and ways to make the most impactful points at the offer phase to maximize your chances of getting a better offer.\'a0
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
Q: What is the cost for the personal service?\

\f2\i \cf4 \strokec4 A: It\'92s a flat fee between $50 - $250 based on the role, industry and company. The fee just covers the analysis and research work.\'a0
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \

\f2\i \cf4 \strokec4 If my tactics and techniques work, It\'92s a 8-13% additional fee on the\'a0delta\'a0between the first and final offer,\'a0ONLY IF\'a0my tactics worked. If they did, I would also deduct the flat fee as a courtesy.
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
Q: I\'92m confused! Can you give an example??\

\f2\i \cf4 \strokec4 A: Of course!
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa388\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \ul \ulc3 Primary Offer\ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa388\partightenfactor0

\f2\i \cf3 At the conclusion of the interview, the company makes you this offer:\'a0
\f0\i0 \

\f2\i Base: $120,000
\f0\i0 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\i Bonus 10%
\f0\i0 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\i Equity: $100,000 (over 4 years)
\f0\i0 \

\f2\i This is a total comp of $120,000 + 12,000 (bonus) + $25,000 annual or =\'a0\cf5 \strokec5 $157,000
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
Let\'92s say this for an IC tech role in a non metro city, the flat fee would be\'a0$150\'a0for me to do the research and analytics and prepare all of your negotiation materials.\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa388\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \ul \ulc3 Final Offer\'a0\ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa388\partightenfactor0

\f2\i \cf3 After I prepare all of your negotiation numerics and business cases, this is what the company comes back with as their best and final offer.\'a0
\f0\i0 \

\f2\i Base: $132,000
\f0\i0 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\i Bonus: 10%
\f0\i0 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\i Equity: $160,000 (over 4 years)
\f0\i0 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\i Sign-on Bonus: $10,000
\f0\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa388\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \ul \ulc3 Calculations\ulnone \
This is a total comp of $132,000 + $13,200 + $40,000 + $10,000\'a0\cf6 \strokec6 =\'a0$195,200\cf3 \strokec3 \
The delta is\'a0\cf6 \strokec6 $195,200\cf3 \strokec3 \'a0-\'a0\cf5 \strokec5 $157,000\cf3 \strokec3 \'a0=\'a0\cf7 \strokec7 $38,200\cf3 \strokec3 \
For this role, it\'92s a 10% on the delta, so my fee would be $3820 - $150 (flat fee refund) or $3670,\'a0\cf7 \strokec7 which I usually just round down to $3500\cf3 \strokec3 \
